The USSR promised Rodzaevsky freedom, safety and then proceeded to arrest and execute him once he trusted them and crossed the border. Germany promised the First Russian National Army that their flag will wave above all of Russia once again. It's important to keep one's promises.

Really the reason of the various Russian volunteers is very simple: Never trust communists. Never collaborate with them and expect anything in return. Never surrender to them. Fight for as long as possible, then run to neutral territory. Refuse to go back no matter what they say.

ROA: Committed treason, fought for the USSR, tortured to death by them.

Cossacks: Trusted the British, handed out to Cheka and tortured to death together with their families in camps.

1st Russian National Army: Fanatical resistance to the end. Everyone who stayed made it alive.

Andrey Vlasov made the mistake to think anything the Soviets told or promised him was true. Betrayed his honor and allies and was then repaid by being tortured to death. Rodzaevsky trusted them. Executed. Only those who didn't surrender or accept peace managed to make it alive.

It's the same reason one finds his childhood drawings endearing, but feels embarrassed by what he wrote a year or two ago; he has overcome the first, but is still stuck at the second in spite of his protests that he's not
